In 1913, the English physicist Henry Moseley observed regularities in the characteristic X-ray spectra of elements. He discovered that a plot of $\sqrt{
u}$ (where $
u$ is the frequency of X-rays emitted) against atomic number ($Z$) yielded a straight line, whereas a plot of $\sqrt{
u}$ against atomic mass did not. This provided experimental evidence that the atomic number is a more fundamental property of an element than its atomic mass. Consequently, Mendeleev's Periodic Law was modified to reflect this discovery.
